	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>EC reviews state of play in ESA EPA negotiations </h1>

			
			<h4>
												25 March 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to an EC information note on the ESA negotiations, talks aimed at concluding a comprehensive EPA continue. These talks involve four governments that have signed interim EPAs (IEPAs), two that have initialled IEPAs, and four which have not initialled an IEPA (the EAC has its own separate agreement). Outstanding issues remaining include the trade coverage of the agreement, export taxes, agricultural safeguards and rules of origin.</p><p>It is maintained that provisions on SPS tariff barriers to trade (TBTs) and trade facilitation have been finalised; progress has been made on both services and agricultural issues; and ‘very constructive’ discussions have taken place on trade-related issues, including sustainable development and competition policy. While both sides acknowledge the importance of development cooperation provisions, ESA negotiators want stronger language on additional funding, while the EC believes the 10<sup>th</sup> EDF resources are sufficient if efficiently and effectively mobilised.</p><p>A companion information note on the EAC EPA negotiations notes the ongoing commitment to negotiating a comprehensive EPA, including agriculture, rules of origin, SPS, TBTs, customs cooperation, and trade facilitation provisions, while postponing negotiations on trade-related rules and trade in services. The note maintains that negotiations on SPS, TBTs, customs cooperation and trade facilitation have been completed, with the chapters on agriculture and economic and development cooperation well advanced.</p><p>According to the EC information note, the pace of negotiations with the EAC is ‘dependent upon the on-going EAC integration process’. It highlights how after a 14-month break negotiations recommenced in September 2011, with a follow-up round in December 2011. The aim is to conclude negotiations in 2012. The main outstanding issues according to the EC are: the MFN provisions, export taxes, rules of origin, dispute settlement and institutional provisions.</p><p>Meanwhile, the debate continues in the EAC on whether to sign and ratify the EAC–EU EPA in its current form. Former Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa has argued at a high-level seminar on the links between the WTO and EPA negotiations that three options face the EAC, and that the pros and cons of each should be carefully considered:</p>
<ul>

<li>Kenya signs the IEPA alone;</li>

<li>all EAC member states sign the IEPA;</li>

<li>no EAC state signs the IEPA.</li>

</ul>
<p>To place the state of EPA negotiations in the wider context, a recent COMESA study revealed that little progress had been made in preparing the Ethiopian economy to participate in the COMESA FTA. The study maintained that ‘the Ethiopian manufacturing industry is neither internationally competitive’ nor showing signs of improvement since the previous similar assessment. However, industries such as ‘sugar, sugar confectionery, cement, lime and plaster ... could bear the competition from outside’. ‘Significant safeguards’ would however be required in other areas.</p><p>A recent World Bank study has argued that fears over the impact of COMESA FTA accession were exaggerated, particularly in terms of the revenue effects. Nevertheless the reality is that Ethiopia is one of eight COMESA members that do not yet participate in the COMESA FTA.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
