<a href="http://xa.yimg.com/kq/groups/6098427/937051862/name/Fact%20Sheet_Interim%20EPA_East%20Southern%20Africa.pdf" target="_self">http://xa.yimg.com/kq/groups/6098427/937051862/name/Fact%20Sheet_Interim...</a></p><p>EC, ‘The Eastern African Community’, EPA Fact Sheet, January 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://xa.yimg.com/kq/groups/6098427/1347129823/name/Fact%20Sheet_EAC_Jan%202012.pdf " target="_self">http://xa.yimg.com/kq/groups/6098427/1347129823/name/Fact%20Sheet_EAC_Ja...</a></p><p><i>Addis Fortune</i>, ‘Ethiopia not ready to Join Free Trade Area after decade’, 29 February 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.tralac.org/2012/02/29/ethiopia-not-ready-to-join-free-trade-area-after-decade/" target="_self">http://www.tralac.org/2012/02/29/ethiopia-not-ready-to-join-free-trade-a...</a></p><p>East African Community, ‘EAC high level workshop on interaction between the WTO and EPA negotiations opens in Arusha’, 14 February 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.thenigerianvoice.com/nvnews/82670/1/eac-high-level-workshop-on-interaction-between-the.html" target="_self">http://www.thenigerianvoice.com/nvnews/82670/1/eac-high-level-workshop-o...</a></p><p><i>East African Business Week</i>, ‘Signing of EPAs risky for region’, 29 February 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.tralac.org/2012/02/29/signing-of-epas-risky-for-region/" target="_self">http://www.tralac.org/2012/02/29/signing-of-epas-risky-for-region/</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>If the Ethiopian government and seven other COMESA members have refrained from participating in the COMESA FTA because of fears over a lack of competitiveness across major economic sectors, then it remains to be seen whether the governments of these countries will favour participation in a broader FTA embracing the EU. The conclusion of a comprehensive EPA will leave the ESA grouping having to face different levels of product coverage and different lists of excluded products. With rules of origin issues a common source of delay at border crossing points, the multiplicity of diverse tariff elimination commitments contained in the various IEPA arrangements in place across the COMESA region is unlikely to facilitate trade in food and even agricultural products. This needs to be seen in the context of EAC and COMESA efforts to put in place NTB monitoring mechanisms, given the existing scale of the problem.</p>
		</div>
		
